# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flow-cytometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Methods of cell sorting fall into two major categories: fluorescence-activated cell sorting (FACS) and immunomagnetic cell sorting.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Due to many years of refinement and increased demand for cell separation however, researchers are working to develop microfluidic sorting devices that have many benefits in comparison to the main types of fluorescence-activated cell sorting and immunomagnetic cell sorting methods.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Fluorescence-Activated Cell Sorting is also known as flow cytometry cell sorting, or by the acronym FACS, which is a trademark of Becton Dickinson and Company.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Fluorescence-activated cell sorting utilizes flow cytometry to separate cells based on morphological parameters and the expression of multiple extracellular and intracellular proteins.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This method allows multiparameter cell sorting and involves encapsulating cells into small liquid droplets which are selectively given electric charges and sorted by an external electric field.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Fluorescence-activated cell sorting has several systems that work together to achieve successful sorting of events of interest.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] These include fluidic, optical, and electrostatic systems.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The disturbances grow exponentially and lead to breakup of the jet in droplets with precise timing.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A cell of interest that should be sorted is measured at the sensing zone and moves down the stream to the breakoff point.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] During the separation of the droplet with the cell in it from the intact liquid jet, a voltage pulse is given to the liquid jet so that droplets containing the cells of interest can be deflected in an electric field between two deflection plates for sorting.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The droplets are then caught by collection tubes or vessels placed below the deflection plates.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Flow cytometry cell-sorting yields very high specificity according to one or several surface markers, but one limitation is constituted by the number of cells that can be processed during a work day.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] For this reason pre-enrichment of the population of interest by immunomagnetic cell sorting is often considered, especially when the target cells are comparatively rare and a large batch of cells must be processed.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Moreover, flow cytometry cell-sorters are complex instruments that are generally used only by well-trained staff in flow cytometry facilities or well-equipped laboratories and, since they are normally large in size, it is not always possible to place them inside a biological safety cabinet.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Therefore, it is not always possible to ensure sample sterility and, since the fluidic systems can be cleaned but are not single-use, there is the possibility of cross-contamination among samples.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Another aspect to be considered is that droplet-generation inside the instrument could lead to aerosol formations that are hazardous to the operator when using infectious samples.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] These last considerations are of particular importance when cell sorting is used for clinical applications -- for example cell therapy -- and should be performed under Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) conditions.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Researchers can use a variety of fluorescent dyes to design multi-color panels to achieve successful, simultaneous sorting of multiple, precisely defined cell types.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Diagram A shows fluorescence-activated cell sorting of negative cell selection (undesired group) and diagram B shows FACS of positive cell selection (desired group).
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Fluorescent dyes can act very differently.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Generally, a fluorescent dye will be excited by a light source (a laser) at a particular wavelength and emit light at a lower energy and longer wavelength.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The most common dyes act by binding to antigens presented on cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Common antigens targeted are clusters of differentiation (CDs).
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] These are specific to a certain type of cell.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] If you can identify which CD is presented on your cells of interest, then you can stain your sample with a fluorescent dye specific to it, and use fluorescence-activated cell sorting to separate the population of interest.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] However, there are many other mechanisms by which fluorescent dyes can act.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Some dyes are able to diffuse across membranes.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] By taking advantage of this property of the dye, users can characterize intracellular activity as well as surface-expression of proteins.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] For example, in dead cells, propidium iodide (PI) can penetrate the nucleus where it binds to DNA.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The fluorescent signal of PI can be used to quantify DNA content for cell cycle analysis or to identify dead cells in a sample.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Certain fluorescent dyes can be used to characterize kinetic intracellular activity rather than fixing cells in formaldehyde and losing viable cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The table below outlines dyes that can be used to measure several parameters of cytotoxicity caused by oxidative stress.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This experimental setup is just one example of the capability of flow cytometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] In FACS systems, these characterized cells can then be sorted and purified for further experiments.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting is also known as immunomagnetic cell separation, immunomagnetic cell enrichment, or magnetic-activated cell sorting, and commonly known by the acronym MACS which is a trademark of Miltenyi GmbH.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting is based on separation of beads passing a magnetic field.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A variety of companies offer different solutions for enrichment or depletion of cell populations.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting provides a method of enriching a heterogeneous mixture of cells based on cell-surface protein expression (antigens).
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This technology is based on the attachment of small, inert, supra-magnetic particles to mAbs specific for antigens on the target cell population.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Cells labelled to these antibody-bead conjugates are then separated via a column containing a ferromagnetic matrix.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] By applying a magnetic field to the matrix, the beads stick to the matrix inside the column and the bead-carrying cells are held back from passing through.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Unlabelled cells can pass through the matrix and are collected in the flow-through.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] To elute the trapped cells from the column, the magnetic field is simply removed.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting therefore enables different strategies for positive enrichment or depletion of cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic beads are small and usually do not interfere with downstream assays, however for some applications it may be necessary to remove them.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Using this separation method up-scaling the cell numbers does not significantly increase processing times, and the sterility of the sample is guaranteed if the cell sorting is performed inside a biosafety cabinet.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] On the other hand, this technique allows cells to separate based only on a single marker, and cannot discriminate between different levels of protein expression (quantitative analysis).
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting has shown to be beneficial when used with NPC (neural progenitor cell) cultures in particular, as it is easier to manage and causes minimal damage to live cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] NPC cultures are especially difficult to work with because live brain cells are sensitive and tend to contaminate each other.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] In order to get clearer results, labs need cleaner materials, meaning more pure NPC lines.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] They used both the immunomagnetic and fluorescence-activated methods to filter out CD271- (useful markers for mesenchymal stem cells) and CD133+ (markers for cancer stem cells) to compare viability of each method.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Immunomagnetic cell sorting has also been used in assistance with reproduction (artificial insemination) and retinal transplant treatment.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] In the case of assisting reproduction, apoptotic sperm cells (dead or damaged cells) are separated out so more non-apoptotic sperm (non-fragmented) cells can be collected and used to increase the subject's chances of fertility.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This type of treatment has shown to be more effective when done repeatedly, increasing the amount of non-apoptotic cells present during insemination.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] In this process, the microbeads were attached to the CD73 enzyme to assist in the separation of PRs (photoreceptors) from retinal organoids.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] When a CD73+ antigen expressed itself with RCVRN+ cells (calcium-binding proteins in the eye), it showed researchers that this combination of CD73+ and RCVRN+ could be used with post-mitotic PR precursors for repair.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Although the study could not verify success in humans, they have the foundation for further research based on the success of pairing non-damaged photoreceptors with a CD73 antigen and the transplantation in rats.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This success in cell separation and pairing through transplantation shows promise for a potential cure for retinal diseases including total blindness.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] So far, only partial vision repair has been reported.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Due to various limitations of fluorescence-activated and immunomagnetic cell sorting devices, a wide range of microfluidic cell-sorting devices have emerged.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A few of these are now commercially available or in commercial development.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Research into microfluidic cell-sorter designs often employ soft lithography techniques utilizing materials such as polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS).
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A key benefit of microfluidic sorters is the potential to perform fluorescence-activated cell sorting in a closed single-use sterile cartridge.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Such a closed cartridge would prevent the exposure of an operator to biohazards through the droplets that are emitted by FACS systems.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Other benefits include reduced impact on cell viability due to reduced hydrodynamic stress on the cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Some published devices show the potential for multi-way sorting, decreased cost of a cartridge due to low-cost manufacturing methods, lower power consumption, and smaller-sized footprints, with some devices being the size of a credit card.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Some have achieved high-purity outputs and rates of up to around 50,000 cells/s.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Microfluidic cell-sorters can be divided into two categories: active and passive.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Active devices deflect individual cells by the cytometric measurements of the cells, made in real time.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Passive devices exploit physical differences between cells in how they interact with the fluid flow or surfaces.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Active microfluidic cell-sorters involve the deflection of individual cells following their measurement using cytometric methods, including fluorescent labelling, light-scatter and image analysis.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Individual cells are deflected by either a force directly on the cell or a force on the fluid surrounding the cells, so that they flow into separate output vessels.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Methods of cell deflection employ several kinds of macroscopic, optical or MEMS (micro-electro-mechanical systems) actuators to deflect a particle or liquid volume within a microchannel.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The fastest of these have demonstrated sort rates in excess of 1000/s and potential maximum throughput rates in some cases approaching those of FACS.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Active microfluidic cell sorting requires similar cytometry instrumentation as fluorescence-activated cell sorting described above.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Active microfluidic cell-sorters have the potential of throughput scaling by parallelisation on chip.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Passive cell sorting uses the behavior of the fluid within the microchannels to alter and separate cells based on size and morphology.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] In curved microfluidic channels, vortices are formed due to the Dean force which locate different sized particles in different cross sectional locations due to the Reynolds number and curve radius of curvature.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Several methods of cell separation and enrichment using antibodies were employed before fluorescence-based and immunomagnetic cell sorting gained popularity.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] These included antibody- and complement-mediated cell separation, polystyrene immunoaffinity devices, and the CellPro CEPRATE® SC System which employed immobilised antibodies in a porous column.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The latter was the first FDA-approved medical device for the separation of hematopoietic stem cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A newer cell separation technique employing antibodies is buoyancy-activated cell sorting (BACS) is a separation technique in which microbubbles bind to cells through antibodies binding to the surface of cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The targeted cells are then removed from a biological sample through flotation.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Single-cell sorting provides a method for sorting a heterogeneous mixture of cells based on intracellular and extracellular properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Single-cell methods enable understanding of cellular properties that may be obscured or non-evident.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The microraft array provides a rapid, cost-effective method for isolating cells, analyzing cells over time, and generating clonal populations with the unique ability to monitor all intra- and extracellular properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] This system is ideal for both adherent and non-adherent cell types.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A single-cell method to observe the response to an external stimulus (in this case, cellular response to a ligand) was studied using a microfluidic device with micro-channel valves to trap a single cell in a chamber.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] A 23-valve system was used for actuation, and fluorescent dye was used in stimulus-response imaging.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Single-cell clustering methods are a series of statistical methods designed by data scientists based on intracellular properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] The process includes Single Cell RNA-Seq data gathering; data preprocessing for clustering; clustering; and evaluations of clustering.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] Scientists apply machine-learning methods (mainly clustering analysis) on the single-cell RNA-Seq data to divide the cells into different categories.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] All the methods are modified to resolve the problems in RNA-Seq data such as dropout of low-expression genes and ambiguous cell markers in the presence of technical biases.
[src:flow-cytometry/cell-sorting] State-of-the-art methods include SC3., CIDR., Seurat and for more detailed information, please refer to the Wiki page: Single Cell RNA-Seq Clustering.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In this process, a sample containing cells or particles is suspended in a fluid and injected into the flow cytometer instrument.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The sample is focused to ideally flow one cell at a time through a laser beam, where the light scattered is characteristic to the cells and their components.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Cells are often labeled with fluorescent markers so light is absorbed and then emitted in a band of wavelengths.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Tens of thousands of cells can be quickly examined and the data gathered are processed by a computer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry is routinely used in basic research, clinical practice, and clinical trials.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometry analyzer is an instrument that provides quantifiable data from a sample.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Other instruments using flow cytometry include cell sorters which physically separate and thereby purify cells of interest based on their optical properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The first impedance-based flow cytometry device, using the Coulter principle, was disclosed in U.S.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Mack Fulwyler was the inventor of the forerunner to today's flow cytometers – particularly the cell sorter.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Fulwyler developed this in 1965 with his publication in *Science*.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The first fluorescence-based flow cytometry device (ICP 11) was developed in 1968 by Wolfgang Göhde from the University of Münster, filed for patent on 18 December 1968 and first commercialized in 1968/69 by German developer and manufacturer Partec through Phywe AG in Göttingen.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] At that time, absorption methods were still widely favored by other scientists over fluorescence methods.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Soon after, flow cytometry instruments were developed, including the Cytofluorograph (1971) from Bio/Physics Systems Inc.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] (later: Ortho Diagnostics), the PAS 8000 (1973) from Partec, the first FACS (fluorescence-activated cell sorting) instrument from Becton Dickinson (1974), the ICP 22 (1975) from Partec/Phywe and the Epics from Coulter (1977/78).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The first label-free high-frequency impedance flow cytometer based on a patented microfluidic "lab-on-chip", Ampha Z30, was introduced by Amphasys (2012).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The original name of the fluorescence-based flow cytometry technology was "pulse cytophotometry" (German: *Impulszytophotometrie*), based on the first patent application on fluorescence-based flow cytometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] At the 5th American Engineering Foundation Conference on Automated Cytology in Pensacola (Florida) in 1976 – eight years after the introduction of the first fluorescence-based flow cytometer (1968) – it was agreed to commonly use the name "flow cytometry", a term that quickly became popular.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Modern flow cytometers are able to analyze many thousands of particles per second, in "real time" and, if configured as cell sorters, can actively separate and isolate particles with specified optical properties at similar rates.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometer is similar to a microscope, except that, instead of producing an image of the cell, flow cytometry offers high-throughput, automated quantification of specified optical parameters on a cell-by-cell basis.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] To analyze solid tissues, a single-cell suspension must first be prepared.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] A flow cytometer has five main components: a flow cell, a measuring system, a detector, an amplification system, and a computer for analysis of the signals.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The flow cell has a liquid stream (sheath fluid), which carries and aligns the cells so that they pass single file through the light beam for sensing.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The detector and analog-to-digital conversion (ADC) system converts analog measurements of forward-scattered light (FSC) and side-scattered light (SSC) as well as dye-specific fluorescence signals into digital signals that can be processed by a computer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The amplification system can be linear or logarithmic.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The process of collecting data from samples using the flow cytometer is termed "acquisition".
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Acquisition is mediated by a computer physically connected to the flow cytometer, and the software which handles the digital interface with the cytometer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The software is capable of adjusting parameters (e.g., voltage, compensation) for the sample being tested, and also assists in displaying initial sample information while acquiring sample data to ensure that parameters are set correctly.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Early flow cytometers were, in general, experimental devices, but technological advances have enabled widespread applications for use in a variety of both clinical and research purposes.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Due to these developments, a considerable market for instrumentation, analysis software, as well as the reagents used in acquisition such as fluorescently labeled antibodies have been developed.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Modern instruments usually have multiple lasers and fluorescence detectors.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The current record for a commercial instrument is ten lasers and 30 fluorescence detectors.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Increasing the number of lasers and detectors allows for multiple antibody labeling, and can more precisely identify a target population by their phenotypic markers.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Certain instruments can even take digital images of individual cells, allowing for the analysis of fluorescent signal location within or on the surface of cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Cells must pass uniformly through the center of focused laser beams to accurately measure optical properties of cells in any flow cytometer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The purpose of the fluidic system is to move the cells one by one through the lasers beam and throughout the instrument.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Fluidics in a flow cytometer with cell sorting capabilities also use the stream to carry sorted cells into collection tubes or wells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] For precise positioning of cells in a liquid jet, hydrodynamic focusing is used in most cytometers.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The cells in suspension enter into the instrument enclosed by an outer sheath fluid.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The sample core is maintained in the center of the sheath fluid.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The sample input rate or how fast the cells flow through to the laser interrogation can be controlled by the pressure of the sheath fluid on the sample core.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Under optimal conditions, the central fluid stream and sheath fluid do not mix.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Acoustic focusing technology is used in some flow cytometers to support hydrodynamic focusing.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Acoustic waves (>2 MHz) pre-focus the sample before introduction to sheath fluid.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The pre-focused sample is then injected into the hydrodynamic core and flowed through the instrument.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This may help with increasing data accuracy under high sample input rates.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Light emitted from fluorophores are in a spectrum of wavelengths, so combining multiple fluorophores may cause overlap.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] To add specificity, optical filters and dichroic mirrors are used to filter and move light to the detectors such as photomultiplier tubes (PMTs) or avalanche photodiodes (APD).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Optical filters are designed as band pass (BP), long pass (LP), or short pass (SP) filters.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Most flow cytometers uses dichroic mirrors and band pass filters to select specific bands of the optical spectrum.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Spectral flow cytometry uses prisms or diffraction gratings to disperse the emitted light of a marker across a detector array.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This allows for the full spectra from each particle to be measured.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The measured spectra from single cells are subsequently unmixed by using reference spectra of all used dyes and the autofluorescence spectrum.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This may allow for a wider panel design and the application of new biological markers.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Imaging flow cytometry (IFC) captures multichannel images of cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Detectors used in imaging platforms can be equipped with charge-coupled device (CCD) or complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) to capture images of individual cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Each fluorochrome has a broad fluorescence spectrum.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] When more than one fluorochrome is used, an overlap between fluorochromes can occur.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This situation is called spectrum overlap, and must be corrected.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] For example, the emission spectrum for FITC and PE is one in which the light emitted by the fluorescein overlaps the same wavelength as it passes through the filter used for PE.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This spectral overlap is corrected by removing a portion of the FITC signal from the PE signals or vice versa.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This process is called color compensation, which calculates a fluorochrome as a percentage to measure itself.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Compensation is the mathematical process by which spectral overlap of multiparameter flow cytometric data is corrected.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Since fluorochromes can have wide-ranging spectrum, they can overlap, causing the undesirable result of confusion during the analysis of data.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This overlap, known as spillover and quantified in the spillover coefficient, is usually caused by detectors for a certain fluorochrome measuring a significant peak in wavelength from a different fluorochrome.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Linear algebra is most often used to make this correction.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In general, when graphs of one or more parameters are displayed, it is to show that the other parameters do not contribute to the distribution shown.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Especially when using the parameters which are more than double, this problem is more severe.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Currently, no tools have been discovered to efficiently display multidimensional parameters.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Compensation is very important to see the distinction between cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The data generated by flow cytometers can be plotted in a single dimension to produce a histogram, or in two-dimensional dot plots, or even in three dimensions.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The regions on these plots can be sequentially separated, based on fluorescence intensity, by creating a series of subset extractions, termed "gates." Specific gating protocols exist for diagnostic and clinical purposes, especially in relation to hematology.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The plots are often made on logarithmic scales.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Because different fluorescent dyes' emission spectra overlap, signals at the detectors have to be compensated electronically as well as computationally.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Data accumulated using the flow cytometer can be analyzed using software.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Once the data is collected, there is no need to stay connected to the flow cytometer and analysis is most often performed on a separate computer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This is especially necessary in core facilities where usage of these machines is in high demand.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Recent progress on automated population identification using computational methods has offered an alternative to traditional gating strategies.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Automated identification systems could potentially help findings of rare and hidden populations.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Representative automated methods include FLOCK in Immunology Database and Analysis Portal (ImmPort), SamSPECTRAL and flowClust in Bioconductor, and FLAME in GenePattern.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (tSNE) is an algorithm designed to perform dimensionality reduction, to allow visualization of complex multi-dimensional data in a two-dimensional "map".
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Fluorescence minus one (FMO) controls are important for data interpretation when building multi-color panels – in which a cell is stained with multiple fluorochromes simultaneously.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] FMO controls provide a measure of fluorescence spillover in a given channel and allow for compensation.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] To generate a FMO control, a sample is stained with all the fluorochromes except the one that is being tested – meaning if you are using 4 different fluorochromes your FMO control must contain only 3 of them (example: fluorochromes – A, B, C, D; FMOs – ABC_, AB_D, A_CD, _BCD).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Cell sorting is a method to purify cell populations based on the presence or absence of specific physical characteristics.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In flow cytometers with sorting capabilities, the instrument detects cells using parameters including cell size, morphology, and protein expression, and then droplet technology to sort cells and recover the subsets for post-experimental use.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The first prototype sorter was built at the Los Alamos National Laboratory (LANL) in 1965 by physicist Mack J.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Fulwyler by joining a Coulter volume sensor with the newly invented ink jet printer.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Live cell cell sorter or fluorescence-activated cell sorter (FACS) was generated by Len Herzenberg, who subsequently won the Kyoto Prize in 2006 for his seminal work.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry cell sorters have a collection system unlike flow cytometry analyzers.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The collection process starts when a sample is injected into a stream of sheath fluid that passes through the flow cell and laser intercepts.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The stream then carries the cell through a vibrating nozzle which generates droplets with most containing either one cell or no cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The charged droplets then fall through an electrostatic deflection system that diverts droplets into containers based on their charge.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In some systems, the charge is applied directly to the stream, and the droplet breaking off retains charge of the same sign as the stream.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The stream is then returned to neutral after the droplet breaks off.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] After collecting, these cells can be further cultured, manipulated, and studied.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry uses the light properties scattered from cells or particles for identification or quantitative measurement of physical properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Labels, dyes, and stains can be used for multi-parametric analysis (understand more properties about a cell).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Immunophenotyping is the analysis of heterogeneous populations of cells using labeled antibodies and other fluorophore containing reagents such as dyes and stains.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] A wide range of fluorophores can be used as labels in flow cytometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Fluorophores, or simply "fluors", are typically attached to an antibody that recognizes a target feature on or in the cell; they may also be attached to a chemical entity with affinity for the cell membrane or another cellular structure.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Each fluorophore has a characteristic peak excitation and emission wavelength, and the emission spectra often overlap.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Consequently, the combination of labels which can be used depends on the wavelength of the lamp(s) or laser(s) used to excite the fluorochromes and on the detectors available.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry uses fluorescence as a quantitative tool; the utmost sensitivity of flow cytometry is unmatched by other fluorescent detection platforms such as confocal microscopy.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Quantum dots are sometimes used in place of traditional fluorophores because of their narrower emission peaks.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Mass cytometry overcomes the fluorescent labeling limit by utilizing lanthanide isotopes attached to antibodies.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This method could theoretically allow the use of 40 to 60 distinguishable labels and has been demonstrated for 30 labels.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Mass cytometry is fundamentally different from flow cytometry: cells are introduced into a plasma, ionized, and associated isotopes are quantified via time-of-flight mass spectrometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Although this method permits the use of a large number of labels, it currently has lower throughput capacity than flow cytometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] It also destroys the analysed cells, precluding their recovery by sorting.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In addition to the ability to label and identify individual cells via fluorescent antibodies, cellular products such as cytokines, proteins, and other factors may be measured as well.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Similar to ELISA sandwich assays, cytometric bead array (CBA) assays use multiple bead populations typically differentiated by size and different levels of fluorescence intensity to distinguish multiple analytes in a single assay.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The amount of the analyte captured is detected via a biotinylated antibody against a secondary epitope of the protein, followed by a streptavidin-R-phycoerythrin treatment.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The fluorescent intensity of R-phycoerythrin on the beads is quantified on a flow cytometer equipped with a 488 nm excitation source.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Concentrations of a protein of interest in the samples can be obtained by comparing the fluorescent signals to those of a standard curve generated from a serial dilution of a known concentration of the analyte.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Commonly also referred to as cytokine bead array (CBA).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Impedance-based single cell analysis systems are commonly known as Coulter counters.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] They represent a well-established method for counting and sizing virtually any kind of cells and particles.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The label-free technology has recently been enhanced by a "lab-on-a-chip" based approach and by applying high frequency alternating current (AC) in the radio frequency range (from 100 kHz to 30 MHz) instead of a static direct current (DC) or low frequency AC field.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This patented technology allows a highly accurate cell analysis and provides additional information like membrane capacitance and viability.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The relatively small size and robustness allow battery powered on-site use in the field.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Measurable factors in cellular analysis and flow cytometry include a diverse set of traits and indicators that provide important insights into cell biology and function.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry techniques can quantify and evaluate these factors, allowing researchers to investigate and analyze various aspects of cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The technology has applications in a number of fields, including molecular biology, pathology, immunology, virology, plant biology and marine biology.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] It has broad application in medicine especially in transplantation, hematology, tumor immunology and chemotherapy, prenatal diagnosis, genetics and sperm sorting for sex preselection.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry is widely applied to detect sperm cells abnormality associated with DNA fragmentation in male fertility assays.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Also, it is extensively used in research for the detection of DNA damage, caspase cleavage and apoptosis.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Photoacoustic flow cytometry is used in the study of multi-drug-resistant bacteria (most commonly MRSA) to detect, differentiate, and quantify bacteria in the blood marked with dyed bacteriophages.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In neuroscience, co-expression of cell surface and intracellular antigens can also be analyzed.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In microbiology, it can be used to screen and sort transposon mutant libraries constructed with a GFP-encoding transposon (TnMHA), or to assess viability.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In protein engineering, flow cytometry is used in conjunction with yeast display and bacterial display to identify cell surface-displayed protein variants with desired properties.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The main advantages of flow cytometry over histology and IHC is the possibility to precisely measure the quantities of antigens and the possibility to stain each cell with multiple antibodies-fluorophores, in current laboratories around 10 antibodies can be bound to each cell.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This is much less than mass cytometer where up to 40 can be currently measured, but at a higher price and a slower pace.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In aquatic systems, flow cytometry is used for the analysis of autofluorescing cells or cells that are fluorescently-labeled with added stains.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This research started in 1981 when Clarice Yentsch used flow cytometry to measure the fluorescence in a red tide producing dinoflagellate.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The next year researchers published flow cytometric measurements of multiple algal species which could be distinguished based on their fluorescence characteristics.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry also allowed marine researchers to distinguish between dimly-fluorescing *Prochlorococcus* and heterotrophic microorganisms, a distinction that is difficult with microscopy-based assessments.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Advances in technology now allow aquatic scientists to use flow cytometers continuously during research cruises and flow cytometers are used to provide images of individual phytoplankton cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Cell proliferation is the major function in the immune system.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Often it is required to analyse the proliferative nature of the cells in order to make some conclusions.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] One such assay to determine the cell proliferation is the tracking dye carboxyfluorescein diacetate succinimidyl ester (CFSE).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] It helps to monitor proliferative cells.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This assay gives quantitative as well as qualitative data during time-series experiments.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This dye binds covalently with the long-lived molecules present inside the cell.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] When the cells divide, the molecules divide too and, the daughter cells possess half the dye than the parent population.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This decrease in the intensity can be visualized by flow cytometry.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In literature, this powerful technique of flow cytometry and CFSE has been used to find the efficiency of T-cells in killing the target cells in cancer such as leukemia.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] In order to visualize the target cell death, both rapid and slow, scientists have used CFSE labelling with antibody staining of certain kinds of cells and fluorescently labelled microbeads.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] This also gave information regarding the proliferation of the target cells upon the treatment of certain cytokines.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Flow cytometry has been used to measure genome sizes, or more precisely: the amount of DNA in a cell or nucleus.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Although genomes can be analyzed with more precision by genome sequencing, this is often difficult due to a high fraction of micro-chromosomes or repetitive sequences which may be missed by sequencing (or which get filtered out during the analysis step when they cannot be assigned to chromosomes).
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] However, flow cytometry is not perfect either.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] The resulting genome sizes may differ based on the dye used.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] An analysis of fish genomes resulted in significantly different genome sizes when propidium iodide (PI) and DAPI were used, respectively.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] For instance, the genome of *Anguilla japonica* was found to contain 1.09 pg of DNA with PI vs.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] Similarly, the genome of *Myxocyprinus asiaticus* was found to contain 2.75 pg of DNA (PI) vs.
[src:flow-cytometry/flow-cytometry] That is, the differences were on the order of 12–14%.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] A **fluorophore** (or **fluorochrome**, similarly to a chromophore) is a fluorescent chemical compound that can re-emit light upon light excitation.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores typically contain several combined aromatic groups, or planar or cyclic molecules with several π bonds.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores are sometimes used alone, as a tracer in fluids, as a dye for staining of certain structures, as a substrate of enzymes, or as a probe or indicator (when its fluorescence is affected by environmental aspects such as polarity or ions).
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] More generally they are covalently bonded to macromolecules, serving as a markers (or dyes, or tags, or reporters) for affine or bioactive reagents (antibodies, peptides, nucleic acids).
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores are notably used to stain tissues, cells, or materials in a variety of analytical methods, such as fluorescent imaging and spectroscopy.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorescein, via its amine-reactive isothiocyanate derivative fluorescein isothiocyanate (FITC), has been one of the most popular fluorophores.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] From antibody labeling, the applications have spread to nucleic acids thanks to carboxyfluorescein.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Other historically common fluorophores are derivatives of rhodamine (TRITC), coumarin, and cyanine.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Newer generations of fluorophores, many of which are proprietary, often perform better, being more photostable, brighter, or less pH-sensitive than traditional dyes with comparable excitation and emission.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The fluorophore absorbs light energy of a specific wavelength and re-emits light at a longer wavelength.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The absorbed wavelengths, energy transfer efficiency, and time before emission depend on both the fluorophore structure and its chemical environment, since the molecule in its excited state interacts with surrounding molecules.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Wavelengths of maximum absorption (≈ excitation) and emission (for example, Absorption/Emission = 485 nm/517 nm) are the typical terms used to refer to a given fluorophore, but the whole spectrum may be important to consider.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The excitation spectrum may be a very narrow or broader band, or it may be all beyond a cutoff level.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The emission spectrum is usually sharper than the excitation spectrum, and it is of a longer wavelength and correspondingly lower energy.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Excitation energies range from ultraviolet through the visible spectrum, and emission energies may continue from visible light into the near infrared region.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] These characteristics drive other properties, including photobleaching or photoresistance (loss of fluorescence upon continuous light excitation).
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Other parameters should be considered, as the polarity of the fluorophore molecule, the fluorophore size and shape (i.e. for polarization fluorescence pattern), and other factors can change the behavior of fluorophores.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores can also be used to quench the fluorescence of other fluorescent dyes or to relay their fluorescence at even longer wavelengths.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] As of 2020, the smallest known fluorophore was claimed to be 3-hydroxyisonicotinaldehyde, a compound of 14 atoms and only 123 Da.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorescence particles like quantum dots (2–10 nm diameter, 100–100,000 atoms) are also considered fluorophores.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The size of the fluorophore might sterically hinder the tagged molecule and affect the fluorescence polarity.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophore molecules could be either utilized alone, or serve as a fluorescent motif of a functional system.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Based on molecular complexity and synthetic methods, fluorophore molecules could be generally classified into four categories: proteins and peptides, small organic compounds, synthetic oligomers and polymers, and multi-component systems.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorescent proteins GFP, YFP, and RFP (green, yellow, and red, respectively) can be attached to other specific proteins to form a fusion protein, synthesized in cells after transfection of a suitable plasmid carrier.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] These fluorophores fluoresce due to delocalized electrons which can jump a band and stabilize the energy absorbed.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] For example, benzene, one of the simplest aromatic hydrocarbons, is excited at 254 nm and emits at 300 nm.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] This discriminates fluorophores from quantum dots, which are fluorescent semiconductor nanoparticles.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] They can be attached to proteins to specific functional groups, such as amino groups (active ester, carboxylate, isothiocyanate, hydrazine), carboxyl groups (carbodiimide), thiol (maleimide, acetyl bromide), and organic azide (via click chemistry or non-specifically (glutaraldehyde)).
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Additionally, various functional groups can be present to alter their properties, such as solubility, or confer special properties, such as boronic acid which binds to sugars or multiple carboxyl groups to bind to certain cations.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] When the dye contains an electron-donating and an electron-accepting group at opposite ends of the aromatic system, this dye will probably be sensitive to the environment's polarity (solvatochromic), hence called environment-sensitive.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Often dyes are used inside cells, which are impermeable to charged molecules; as a result of this, the carboxyl groups are converted into an ester, which is removed by esterases inside the cells, e.g., fura-2AM and fluorescein-diacetate.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] The following dye families are **trademark groups**, and do not necessarily share structural similarities.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores have particular importance in the field of biochemistry and protein studies, for example, in immunofluorescence, cell analysis, immunohistochemistry, and small molecule sensors.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorophores have been used with polymers in different ways and for many types of applications in different fields such as biochemistry, analytical chemistry, material science, and nanochemistry.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] For example, peptide-RAFT agents tagged with 5,6-carboxyfluorescein have been used to synthesize polyacrylamide, polyacrylate and polystyrene with possible applications for analysis of cellular uptake of different sized polymers.
[src:flow-cytometry/fluorophore] Fluorescent polyolefins, such as fluorescent polyethylene, have been synthesized and explored as materials due to their possible applications in fluorescent probes, LEDs, information storage and encryption devices, cell imaging, plastic sorting, and quantification of recycled plastic.
[src:flow-cytometry/immunophenotyping] Immunophenotyping is a very common flow cytometry test in which fluorophore-conjugated antibodies are used as probes for staining target cells with high avidity and affinity.
[src:flow-cytometry/immunophenotyping] This technique allows rapid and easy phenotyping of each cell in a heterogeneous sample according to the presence or absence of a protein combination.
